title: For Sale:  Husqvarna CG63 Swedish Target Rifle For Sale (6.5x55)
postcontent: I have a very nice Husqvarna CG 63 Swedish target rifle chambered in 6.5x55 for sale.  These rifles are hard to find these days and rarely come up for sale.  These rifles are well known for their quality and accuracy.  Here is some information on how these rifles were produced: The CG 63 is a match grade rifle.  These rifles were built by Carl Gustaf, from surplus m/94 carbines and m/96 rifles. The CG 63 featured a new free-floating heavy barrel, a new pistol-grip stock and a micrometer aperture sight. The cocking piece was modified to reduce mass and stroke, the trigger was ribbed, and the trigger guard was serrated.  Armorers chose the best possible parts to outfit the CG 63 rifles, since these rifles were used by members of the rifle organisation 'Frivilliga Skytterörelsen' (FSR) for competition shooting.  The rifles were designed for shooting at 300 meters, but the fully adjustable diopter sights allow shooting from 100 to 600 meters (yards).  Rear sight diopter elevation tabs can allow shooting out to 1000 meters (yards) for some models. Here are the specifics for this rifle:  This rifle has a fully adjustable Soderin rear diopter sight and a front globe sight with an aperture insert.  I have 2 additional aperture inserts with different aperture sizes for the front sight that will be included.  I would classify the bore to be in good condition and is shiny with minimal chamber wear.  Rifling is strong with some light frosting.  The muzzle is very tight.  The stock is in very good condition with a few small dings.  The bolt matches the receiver.  (It is typical for other parts not to match on these rifles, since the armorers were hand picking the best parts for each of these rifles).  The only defect with this rifle is that there is a crack in the front globe sight base.  This crack was repaired and I have shot it many times with no problems.  These front globes are easily replacable, but I have seen no need to replace this one, since it functions perfectly.  One unusual feature of this rifle is that it has a 1943 Husqvarna receiver and bolt.  The vast majority of these rifles have older Carl Gustav receivers.  Some Swedish shooters claimed the Husqvarna receivers were more accurate, and were highly sought after.  I believe that this particular rifle was converted to a CG 63 in 1970, but can't be sure.  The rifle is chambered for the very accurate Swedish 6.5x55 mm round.  This round shoots flat, is accurate, has low recoil, and is easily reloadable.  I hate to sell this rifle, but I need to fund another purchase and will let it go, since I have another one.  I have more photos available upon request.  I can be reached by text at REDACTED or by response through the Armlist website.  I have a hearing loss and cannot answer phone calls, but will respond by text.

title: For Sale:  One-of-a-Kind Kimber Super Match II 1911
postcontent: This one-of-a-kind Kimber Super Match II 1911 pistol, featuring exquisite hand engraving and “SUPER 1911” Serial number is one of two Kimber firearms being featured for the first time in the history of the SHOT Show auction. Featured in a separate SHOT Show auction on ARMSLIST.com is a Kimber SuperAmerica .308 Traditional rifle, hand-engraved and offering serial number “SUPER308”. The special pair not only marks the first time that Kimber firearms have been featured in the SHOT Show auction, it is also the first time that a themed handgun and rifle have ever been offered by one manufacturer. The rifle and pistol share the “SUPER” serial number theme to emphasize their “Super” status among target shooters, hunters and collectors.This Super Match “SUPER1911” is hand-engraved by Rob Bunting of Baron Engraving in Trumbull, Connecticut. Rob is a highly skilled and creative engraver who has engraved some of the most popular firearms in SHOT Show auction history.In explaining the engraving pattern he featured on the Super Match II 1911 (and the SuperAmerica .308 rifle), Rob said, “First off, 1911's are one of my favorites to work on! When I saw the serial number was special, I thought I would try something a little different for this one. I tend to do leafy scroll, which I like very much, but I wanted to simplify the look this time around. This pattern has a very strong central spine with leaves placed more formally at regular intervals. The spine receives very little shading and the leaves are heavily shaded and cross-hatched, which creates a very strong contrast in the design. I think that is what makes it nice. I also removed a fair amount of background from between the scrolls and put in a nice strong punch dot pattern down to increase the contrast. Black fill in the cuts makes the whole thing pull together and pop.” The new Super Match II 1911is designed for competition right out of the box with all new features and an accuracy guarantee of one-inch five-shot groups at 25 yards. The .45 ACP features Kimber adjustable sights, fancy walnut grips and match grade trigger. Barrel length is five inches and weight is 39 ounces with unloaded 8-round magazine. You are bidding only on the Kimber 1911 in this auction. title: For Sale:  Springfield 1866 Allin Conversion
postcontent: Nice Springfield Allin Conversion, Marked 1866 on Top of receiver and 1865 on Side plate. Barrel length 36.6 inches. The rifle was chambered for the powerful centerfire .50-70 Government cartridge (.50 caliber 450-grain (29 g) bullet; 70 grains (4.5 g) of black powder). (Wiki): The Springfield Model 1866 was the second iteration of the Allin-designed trapdoor breech-loading mechanism. Originally developed as a means of converting rifled muskets to breechloaders, the Allin modification ultimately became the basis for the definitive Model 1873, the first breech-loading rifle adopted by the United States War Department for manufacture and widespread issue to U.S. troops. The Model 1866 corrected problems encountered with the prototypical Model 1865, in particular a simplified and improved extractor and a superior .50 caliber centerfire cartridge (the Model 1865 used a .58 caliber rimfire cartridge with mediocre ballistics), among many other less significant changes. It employed a robust version of the "trapdoor" breechblock design originated by Erskine S. Allin, Master Armorer of the Springfield Armory. Approximately 25,000 .58 caliber Springfield Model 1863 rifled muskets were converted by Springfield Armory for use by U.S. troops, the barrels being relined and rifled to .50 caliber and the trapdoor breech system affixed. The rifle was chambered for the powerful centerfire .50-70 Government cartridge (.50 caliber 450-grain (29 g) bullet; 70 grains (4.5 g) of black powder).

title: For Sale/Trade:  Aero Precision AR15  LOADED UP!
postcontent:
Looking to stretch out your varmint rifle without paying absurd prices for ammo (see .22-250, .220 Swift, .204 Ruger, etc..).  Then here is your gun.  I built this gun to easily shoot 500-600 yards and further.
 
Up for sale is an Aero Precision matched upper and lower, stuffed with all kinds of extras that will make shooting all day a treat.  This gun has never seen a bullet fired, or even chambered and all items were purchased brand new.  It would be an ideal rig for prairie dog, small varmint hunting, punching paper or ringing steel at longer distances.

The Lower receiver:
The receiver is an Aero Precision Gen 2 and has a Black Rain Ordnance LPK in it.  The enhanced trigger guard is by Core-15.  The stock is a black Magpul PRS and for the life of me I cant remember the manufacturer of the tube.  The magazine release bar is a Strike Industries model and the button itself is by Odin and provides a shorter reach and a larger surface to make dropping the magazine easier.  The gun has an Extended Bolt Release made by Phase 5 and is one of my favorite accessories on the gun.  The take down pins are made by Strike Industries and provide a bigger surface to aid in removal.  The selector is by Hera Arms and is a 60* short throw and is also ambidextrous.  The grip is a Magpul MOE.  The drop in trigger group is an Elftmann 3-Gun trigger.  It is adjustable between 2.5-4lbs and is, in a word, "AMAZING".  Read up on them for full details as I dont remember all of the specs off the top of my head.  The trigger pins are KNS Anti-Roll and are often used with drop in triggers.
The Upper receiver:
The upper is an Aero Precision M4 Enhanced.  These are great because the barrel nut that also holds the rail for most guns, is actually part of the upper receiver.  By having all one piece, you never have to worry about it loosening or twisting.  It cant.  The actual barrel nut is actually inside the rail mount and slightly recessed.  Another nice thing about the enhanced receiver is that the forward assist roll pin has been replaced by a hex head screw in pin.  The forward assist and the dust cover on this are from Strike Industries.  The 15" MLOK handguard is also Aero Precision and is solid as a rock due to its mount.  The barrel on this beast is a Wilson Combat Super Sniper .223 Wylde (shoot everything from .223 Rem, 5.56, and .223 Wylde with no issues) with a 1:8 (best of both worlds and allows for a wider variety of bullets to be accurately fired) twist that is 20" long.  It is a .936 diameter and therefore, it also has a Wilson Combat Adjustable Gas Block.  Obviously, since I havent shot the gun yet, it has not been tuned for this barrel, BCG, and buffer setup.  Speaking of BCG's, this one is the NiB (Nickel Boron) offering from Fail Zero and it is full auto rated.  The charging handle is a Strike Industries and has the extended latch for easier operation.  The gas system on this gun, as you can imagine for a 20" barrel, is a rifle length system.Will include a new magazine and a box of ammo as well. I am also open to selling the upper or lower by themselves if someone is interested in just one or the other.  Let me know what you have in mind.
I can accept Debit and Credit Cards for the small fee of 2% as well.
